{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_jacobs_ver01/data/sn84020645/00513684253/1908032901/1160.xml":{"full_text":"Some of features of\nModern Commercial\nBuilding*\n\nto rm Matte* to Hetarbt. at Whit*\nBautlM M<k With Blac Trlm\nThaatrteal Performance.\nTha formal eprtng opening of Mont\ngomery Fair will be obeerved Mon\nf. day morning. not only by a dlaplay of\ntha immense stork that la offered the\npatron* and the customers of the great\nemporium of Montgomery, but with a\npublic dlaplay of theatrical entertain\nment.\nIt la not. of couraa. the flret tlm#\nthat Montgomery Fair haa been openeJ.\nTomorrow will be only a formal re\nception of the people of Montgomery,\nwho will ba entertained with the free\nf'. performance of \"Galatea\" aa well aa\nwith a dlaplay of the building and Ita\neontenta.\nTo receive the gueata. not only the\nampdoyes. but the managers of Mont\ngomery Fair will be In the \"receiving\nline\"\nThe building Itself la of a fine type\n,.\u2014i\u2014-i-..\nIt wa| accomplished with a complete\nness of effect regards light and With\na consummate skill in the ornamanta\ntlon of the mechanical apparatus re\nquired to afford It tKst are gdmirabls\nfor Ingenuity and tasto. Just a glimpse\nof The Fair\" when the light are on,\nconvinces that IMS's Imitation of the\nday-star Is utilised to Its highest po\ntentiality.\nIn the seoend-story there Is Just as\nbright and pure an atmosphere. The\nsecond floor Is the home of the ladles'\nsuit and millinery department. Down\nstairs Is Ih* rush and fun of bargain\nhunting\u2014and at Montgomery Fair\nthere Is no does season on bargain\nhunting; on the second floor patrons\ncalmly and with discriminating nicety,\nleisurely select things to wear. Just\nto make the proceedings easy and\noomfortabl*. there Is devoted a large\nproportion Of space to afford to women\nbeing titled not only privacy and every\nnecessary adjunct to satisfaction In\nmaking purchase, but room for retting.\nThe system of enunciattve bells, for\nInstance; when a woman enters a try\ning-on room, there le no loud cry for\na Utter; a button la pressed, for off\nsomewhere a silvery tinkle seeme to\necho beck from fairyland. Out of the\nfairyland cornea a fairy akilted In the\nmaking of clothee. Then the work Is\ndone. If there Is sewing ordered 1*\nmay be despatched handily, for the\nsewing rooms are hard by.\nWithin close range, too. are tha dis\nplays of lingerie suits. They are\nmade a feature. And. as If to com\nriarry Danziger, the Popular Montgomerian, Who Has Been Such a\nFactor in the Success of the Fair.\nof what may b\u00ab called commercial\narchitecture. Its (root, on Court Square,\nstretches wide and high. ot chaate\nwhite enamel brick with blue trim\nmings. It 1\u00ab topped by a handsome par\napet and far ornamentation has tour\nbeautiful heads of medallion form. Not\nthe leant attractive of Its beauties Is\nthe bread display of plats glass win.\ndown, extended, except for the vesti\nbules entirely across the front of Mont\ngomery rail- The vestibules extend\nwithin the building and reach swing\ning plate glass doors.\ni tits building Is entirely modern in\nconstruction, sad is fireproof. It has\na frontage of 100 feet on Court Square\nand has a depth of 140 foot. It con\ntains four stories and the basement.\nIt Is tbs Interior of the building that\nto most admirable. Within the walls\nno contrivances or piss that lends for\ncomfort snd safety of employe snd pat\nron, and for offectlvonoos of display of\nmerchandise as well as convenience in\nhandling it. has been omitted. Light\nand ventilation of exact dagree of san\nitation and hygiene are afforded la\nevery nook and corner, as well as In\nthe wider spaces of the building, in\nWhich there has bean employed every\nScheme to economise space snd yet lav\nishly allow ease of movement through\naa Immensity of materials and a\nthrong of buoy employes and eager\ncustomers that with less of system\nwould be but insurmountable obstacles\nPad an animated hurly-burly.\nThe Ground Floor.\nUpon the ground floor, entering from\n(Court Square, the patrons of the Fair\nand themselves within a hall whose\npxteasivensss of nearly an acre is hard\nly realised because of the remarkable\narrangements. Aisles are so wide that\n{there Is no possibility of a crush, for\n\u2022While the departments even upon one\nfloor are numerous, they are not Ir\nregular; wide are the passageways on\neach side of the generously large dis\nplay tables on which are the big\natocks of silks, dressgoods, embroider\nies. laces, white goods, linens, wash\nfabrics, handkerchiefs, hosiery, gloves,\nclothing, men's furnishings, notions\nneckwears, parasols.\nThs entire space across the rear of\nthe first floor Is utilised for the shoe\nliHfoMWit for men. women and chib\n'fret.\nKot that only the arrangement of\nthe floor spaces on the ground story,\nor. Indeed, on any story, Is admirable.\nWhs Ulterior decorations are beautify\nThe flntsh la In mahoganlsed birch\nfrom collar to roof, and It affords for\nartistically grouped and placed stuffs\nof many colors a wonderfully fine back\nground. Walls, tables and other store\nfurniture are of the same material, de\nsigned simply and with striking effect\nbf strength and richness. And at the\nTear is a stairway of singular beauty.\nHere may beat be mentioned the\nwonderful Illumination of the building.\nTo illuminate a building of such\n-size as Is Montgomery Fair, as It\nStands In the middle of a block with\n(tall buildings hedging It about. Is an\narchitectural problem of singular dif\nficulty. But the solution of the prob\nlem. however hard It may have been to\n-get at. was made completely and Anally\nipy the men who planned Montgomery\nSfelr. And it was very simple, too\u2014\nafter it had been done. With the use\nof a primatlc construction of window\ngrtam, the multiplied sunlight until, j\nilt not made darkness visible, as It is\nsaid In a line of Milton, but made\nibrtghtoess darkened; some of the lights\nare so Intense that they have to be\nsoftened with double shades.\n1 Ths artificial Illumination of tha\nbuilding naturally\u2014It there is a pun\nIs that, It la both incidental and acci\ndental\u2014tha artificial Illumination, of\ncourse, offered no unusual dinculttea.\nWith the softened brilliance of 148 area\ndad hundreds of incandescent globes.\nplete the fitting: department, there are\nmade on the same floor the display of\nmuslin underwear and corsets; and ev\nerything that belongs In ready-made\ngarments Is set forth on tables and In\nglass cases so furnished with varnish\nand bright metal that It Is a pleasure\nto look as well as to buy.\nIt Is on this floor, also, that there\nare a rest roopi and telephone and\nmaids and writing desks and all othec,\nmaterial and personal comforts.\nBut perhaps the chiefest of all the\nthings, from the feminine 'point of\nview, that the floor offers Is millinery\u2014\nhats and places to try them on. As\nmuch privacy for trying on a hat Is\nafforded ss for trying on a dresa\nThe Hattery\u2014and that Is a word\nthat ought to have been used In\n\u201cAlice In Wonderland,\" Is absolutely\ncomplete.\nFour New York, and London, and\nParis etvlea are brought and from the\nstock Montgomery women may choose.\nCertainly In the South, probably in\nthe United States, there Is not afforded\na more complete exhibition.\nThe third floor comprises two very\ndistinct departments: there are things\nfor sale, and there are ofllces for the\nmanagement of the big store. It Is\nthe home of carpets and ruga and furn\niture and mattings and draperies and\nfor their display there are arranged\nseparate compartments. The prospect\nive customer dees not have to look\nat half a vard of carpet or a handful\nof curtains to see what he wants: car\npets are spread, furniture la placed\nand curtains are hung so that the en\nsemble may be criticised. There Is an\nenormous amount of aach kind of\nfurnishing but It can be aeen as quick\nly as eggs In a neat\nThle la made a point of display.\n\"Bee tt Is as It will look when It la\nI being used.\"\nAnd In each of the display depatt\nments the ealemen speak with aa com\nplete Intelligence as If he were merely\nnaming a price or a grade of mater\nial.\nAs for the ofllces. they are wonder\nful In their r\\mpletenea*. From that\nof the manager to that of the clerks\nwho superintend the details every de\nvice for quick and accurate service\nla afforded. The telephone exchange,\nfor example, ts complete In Itself. From\nthe general public telephone system\nthere are seventeen wires: In (he house\n'phone system there are twenty live\nIngenious \"credit system\u201d addltons\nthat destroy Time and make Space a\nparlor word. The mall order system,\ncomplicated as It might seem at first\nglance. Is so perfected that It Is mere\nly a question of expressing '#nt by\nthe customer and satisfying It by\nsalesmen.\nThe stock of these things comprises\nthe most complete lines that may be\nhad.\nThe fourth floor Is utilised to house\nthe dressmakers. It le their house and\ntheir home for the day. If they\nohooee they may eat there for a pri\nvate dining room, with gas stove, with\ntable* and service le offered for them\nand all other female employes.\nNext to them are the receiving\nrooms for new stock. Each of the de\npartments is alloted a separate room.\nThen there Is the baaemont. It Is\nnot to be disregarded as a mere home of\nheavy air and ehllllng damps. At Is as\nwell v\u00abntll*te<l aa the rest of the build\ning. It is a sort of revelation to shop\nping Montgomery. It contains *11 the\ncrockery and housefurnlshings. kit\nchen ware, and a thousand other\nthings that would read like the cata\nlogue of a mail order house. And\ntt Is as cool la summer, as warm In\nwinter, as any place In the world. It\nla of itself a great big floor that at\ntracts and entrances.\nOne of the notable features of the\n4\nMontgomery\u2014The City Which\nHas Come to Herself.\n\"Montgomery at this time 1* doing more building than any other city\nof it else in the United States.*'\nIn the midst of the recent financial panic, the correspondent of Well\nknown building journal used that sentence. An accurate comparison of the\nbuilding operations of all the cities of the United States of the class of\nMontgomery la impossible, but If any one of them IS doing what Montgom\nery Is. It Is doing something wonderful. Alabama\u2014the South, does not re\nalise what the Capital City of the State Is doing. Visitors to the city open\ntheir eyes In amassment.\nMontgomery is excelling Birmingham lti building skyscrapers. When\nthe buildings now being rushed to completion are finished. Montgomery will\nhave wrested the eky-scraplng championship of Alabama from Birmingham.\nAnd what is more, the well Informed cltlsen of Montgomery believes that\nmore residences are In process of construction in Montgomery than In Bir\nmingham or any other city of the State. For three years the building ad\nvance of the city has been little short of iqarvellous.\nThe Advertiser this morning publishes pictures of the notable build\nings of Montgomery which are in process of construction, or which have\nbeen finished for a few weeks. The array is enough to give a new feeling\nof pride to the patriotic citlxen of Montgomery. Now let any city of Mont\ngomery class match It.\nThe first of Montgomery's skyscrapers is the First National Bank Build\ning-twelve steries high. A description of it has been published previously\nIn The Advertiser. The Interior of this building la especially handsome, all\nfloors being finished in marble. With the exception of the Candler Build\ning In Atlanta it is perhaps the most handsomely appointed office building\nIn the South.\nThe Oay-Teague Building. In which the new hotel is to be located, is\nwell under way. All the steel has been put in place and the outer casing\nof brick and stone has been laid. The Bell Building, a twelve-story office\nstructure, is being rushed to completion.\nFor the first time a picture is printed of the splendid structure of the\nFirst Baptist Church, which is near enough completed for its occupancy\nby the congregation. This Is one of the most impressive piles In the State,\nand perhaps no city has a handsomer or more Imposing church. Without\nany blowing of horns or fanfare of praise, a citizen of Montgomery has\njust erected the large and Impressive Empire Building, designed to furnish\nthe demand lor a modern apartment house. In the past year no less than\nfour fine apartment houses have been erected in Montgomery.\nThe pictures and the stories printed this morning carry no Information\nof the Immense building operations in progress in the residential section of\nthe city. The figures are not easily obtainable. But no man who travels\nabout the streets of the city outside of the business district need to fee told\nof the extensive building. It la going on in every section of the city.\nThe house which three years ago was a suburban residence is now a city\nhome. The natural limits of th\u00ab city have been pushed back so fast that\none can hardly keep track of them.\nAnd this In a so-called financial panic. Montgomery's day was a little\nlate in coming. But the elty IS now making up for lost time.\nThe new 'sky line of Montgomery's business district Is shown. Look at tt.\nSee a city that has suddenly come to Itself.\nMontgomery Fair U that It has two\nprominent entrance* that on Court\nSquare it of courae the more promi\nnent, but on Dexter Avenue thare te a\ndoor that leads to what ie called the\nArcade. It le a atore In Iteelf.\nOn the first floor It haa the jewelry\ndepartment where are olfered all Itlnde\n*f novelties sold by a regular Jewelry\nStore. Then there are books, the lat\nest copyright* at lowest prices: there\nla stationery. There Is a confection\nery department; there la an art-needle\nwork department that Is being made a\nspecialty: there are toilet good* There\nIs a pattern department with a special\npattern magaslne published monthly.\nOf course the Arcade has direct con\nnection with the main building.\nOn the eecond floor of the Arcade Is\nthe toy department and a departure\nhere made la In the perennial opening\nof the floor. Toys there don\u2019t wait for\nChristmas and Santa Claus; they are\neternally on the move, now coming In\ncarload, again leaving In deltvory\nwagons to make glad the hearts of\nyoung Americana. With the toys are\nbaby-buggies for the young ones that\nare going to play with the toys.\nOn the third floor of the Arcade are\nspecially arranged compartments for\nthe display of the stock of furntturs\nwhich is extensive m price and quality\nand quantity.\nThe mechanical contrlvancae utilised\nIn the Montgomery Fair are perhaps\nof chfefest interest. Connecting the\nbasement and the street for delivery\npurposes there la a hydraulic lift To\nreceive freight there Is the moet mod\nern chute from the sidewalk to base\nment. For transference of passengers\nand freight from one floor to another\nthere are three elevators of the finest\nthat can be had. To expedite the dis\ntribution of paresis there is a special\nparcels chute for the prompt and safe\ndelivery of packages to the general de\nlivery department in the baeement. The\ndelivery system le as prompt In the de\nlivery of a spool of cotton or a suite of\nfurniture.\nAnd to see that all machinery Is\never In working order a special me\nchanic is always In th\u00ab building to\nlend first aid.\nTo purify the atmosphere there are\nexhaust fans which operate on all\nfloora A system of Ice water that\nlooks like a city water works system,\nfans, lights, rest rooms, toilets and\nprivate lockers are afforded to em\nployea\nAnd In connection with that regard\nfar employe'* health and happiness\nmay be mentioned one of the secrets of\nths success of the Fair; the many men\nand women who work there are triad\nto work there. Some of them have\nbeen there thirty years; more for\ntwenty years; there ars many who\nhave been there fifteen yesrs.\nTo render the store safe from Are\nthere la a apacia] sprlnklar system. If\nthere la enough heat to make trouble\nwhen a Are Is Incipient, the sprinklers\nautomatically spray tha endangered\nsection of tho building and tell the ef\nAclent Are department of Montgomery\nthat something is going to happen. In\nthe meantime the big tank on top of\ntho building la gotten Into service.\nTo protect patrons and employes\nthere Is a Are tower. It le not a Are\nescape In the outside sense of tho\nword. It Is within the building but\nshut off with big walls that would\nmake* It aafe In any contingency. It\nh*a etairway not ladders. It Is. In case\nof Are. automatically cut off from oth\ner parts of the bulld.ng.\nThe Montgomery Fall la a depart\nment store. It is not only a place\nwhere all things may be bought; H Is\na. place where all the best things can\nbe bought\nF\u00bbu are a somnambulist and take\na walk and there wake, you will think\nyou are 1A New York. You will be\nmerely In SltUe old Montgomery, as It\nU now and as it ought to be; the\nMontgomery that is hundreds of thou\nsands ahead of the boastful cities of\nthe South.\nMontgomery Fair is a feature of\nMontgomery. It has been here many\nyears; It le one of the old things that\nstand for the spirit as well as the pro\ngress of Montgomery. Charles B. Cast\nner. of Nashville. Is president. Harry\nDanxiger of Montgomery, general man\nager, and Leon Ashley is cashier.\nMr. Danxiger has charge of the buy\ning. which Is done personally by the\n\u00abcor0 of department leaders, and of the\nxslllng which Is done not only by the\nsame leaders but by the many Salesmen\nunder them. Mr. Ashley supervises\nIhe kinetic Anances, if such a phrase\nmay b. made, of the Montgomery Fair.\nIn the personnel of the management\nJf Montgomery Fsir has chief Inter,\ntst. of course. In Mr. Danxiger and Mr\nAshlay.\nPerhaps to Mr. Danxiger. more than\n(r.itlxsrt oa Page Tea.)\ni\n\u2018\u2022y V,\njrtistic Court Square Front of the Beautiful New Building Erected by The Montgomery Fair to Accom\nmodate ita Constantly Growing Business.\nMONTGOMERY\u2019S FUTURE\nBy C. Grotvenor Dawe\nSuch remarkable chances have come\nIn the physical appearance of Mont\ngomery within the past few years at\nthis moment, when The Advertiser Is\ndrawing special attention to these\nchanges. It Is fitting to consider what\nthey portend for the future.\nThe pathway along the coming years\nIs plainly visible. A city's growth Is\nboth a cause and an effect. Buildings\ncome Into existence through human\nhands because a need Is recognized. In\nsuch a sense a city Is an effect. It Is\nequally true that one building or style\nof building will lead to others. In\nsuch a sense a city's growth Is a cause\n\u2022of greater growth. Montgomery shows\nthis. When, after long effort, the first\nmodern office building of this city be\ncame a fact, It sounded the knell of\nevery building whose equipment of\ncomfort was less, and while.the trans\nformation of the city Into modern form\nmay take time. It Is as certain as the\nruing of the sun. There Is, at this mo\nKfl!#\nfoollsh competition for one property\nowner efter another to tempt tenant*\nby Improved condition*; for there would\nonly be a certain number of tenant*\navailable and hence the competition\nand growth would be fictitious. But\nthe experience of the pant seven year*\n\u25a0how* clearly that Montgomery, instead\nof standing still, 1* moving forward by\nleaps. In 1900, we had 20,0M popula\ntion; In 1*07 we probably had *2,000\nwithin the city lllmt* and unquestion\nably had this number If the outskirts\ncould be Included. This growth has\nbeen steady and normal, due to the\nfact that Montgomery I* the most con\nvenient railroad centre of the entltre\nState and due to the fact that the State\nas a whole le progressing rdpldly and\nattracting the attention of new capi\ntal. new enterprises and In turn, at\ntracting to the Capital City all branch\nes that depend upon a large population\nand lte needs. It Is well at this mo\nment, when problems of depletion may\nconfront some of our property owners.\nThe First Baptist jChurch, One of the. Most Splendid Church Edifices\nin the South.\nnent, not an attractive room left un\ndented In the Ftret National Bank\n>ulldlng. and by next October It Is not\ninreasonable to expect the Bell bulld\nng to be comfortably filled. Neither\n>f these events in the history of\ndontgomery can take place at the pres\nint moment without subjecting- the old\norra of office building to d severe\ntrain, thus compelling the owners of\n>artlally or totally emptied property\no considtft' ways and means of produc\nng an Income from their property by\nleans of attractive buildings with more\nnodefn equipment.\nSolid Growth Assured.\nIf Montgomery were to remain fixed\ns to population, then it would be\nto speak reassuringly regarding the fu\nture and thua help them to realize that\nnew buildings will bring new tenants,\nand new tenants new business In an\never-widening clrlcle. In other words.\nJudging by the tremendous accession\nof population* In the last seven years,\ndue to no fraudulent booming methods',\nbat due to actual unused opportunity\nin this Southern State, we are Jus\ntified in declaring for Montgomery a\ncontinued development, year after year;\nas Its convenience becomes better\nknown and understood, and the State\nof which It is the capital begins to\nsurrender, even in part .the wealth that\nhas been for ages burled in Its hills or\nthat has remained unseen and unap\npreciated In its solJ.\nMontgomery's Position Caique.\nIt Is safe to foretell for Montgomery\nin the next ten years a greater change\nin- Its cuter appearance than has taken\nplace In the last ten years and a\ngreeter-growth In Its population; for\nin ten years' influences will be at work\nto make Montgomery\u2019s position abso\nlutely sure and unassailable among the\nleading cities of the South. Some\noitles depend upon agriculture, and the\nneeds that go with agriculture; some\ncities depend upon manufacturing en\nterprises. Particularly do we find such\nin New England where raw 'material\nanl Coil have to be brought from afalr\nand then again the finished material\nhauled Sway to a distant market. But\nMontgomerKd position Is unique. If\nthe agricultural region round about'\nhere were developed to Its full possi\nbilities, then Montgomery would be a\ngreat city upon that basis alone. If\nMontgomery's advantageous position\nas a manufacturing centre were devel\nopen to Its full, the city would be great\non that basis alone. But nature and\nopportunity vie with each other In\nplacing before the seeing eyes of the\nawakened Montgomery an expectation\nof .being great from both causes. In\nfadt. the opportunity Is so remarkable\nhere that if the men of Montgomery\nthemselves were to close their eyes de\nliberately to that which Is positively\nbefore us, there would neverthelss be\na great move of people and of enter\nprise to this point by those who see\nbetter than we here locally.\nWhite Men Coming.\nOne of th'e most hopeful signs of\nMontgomery's future greatness Is the\nfact that here and there a plantation\nowner Is coming to realize that the\nold method of handling lands, permit\nting them to deteriorate under care\nless treatment. Is \u201cplayed out\" and that\nsome new method must he found or\nour plantation owners will be land\npoor. The solution of the problem, as\naffecting Montgomery, as bringing Im\nmediate financial benefit to the plan\ntation owner, as providing money for\ninvestment in more profitable lines,\nrests in selling land outright In small\nareas to white settlers, who will come\nhere promptly enough if the opening\nexists; for the stern winters of the\nNorth snd the long unproductive sea\nsons are turning the eyes of thousands\nsouthward, now that intelligence has\nlead them to realize that the South is\nhealthy instead of hopelessly un\nhealthy, and has great opportunities\nInstead of being narrow In Its outlook.\nIf all the forties within a few miles\nof Montgomery were In the hands of\nthrifty white men. with proper school\ning facilities for their children. Mont\ngomery would be greatly enriched.\nFrom this source. Montgomery will be\nenriched In a few years; for the pres\nent order of things is passing away\nand cannot long remain, as it rests on\nthe defective principle of absentee\nlandlordism.\nOur Adraatageowe Pasltkoa.\nFrom the viewpoint of manufactur\ning. Montgomery's future Is certain\nbecause It forms a most convenient\npoint for dealing with raw products\nof the mineral belt before they pass\nout Into the commerce of the world\nthrouugb the porta of Savannah. Pea\nNEW HOME OF\nFIRST CHURCH\nMagnificent Structure\nfor Baptists.\nONE OF THE SOUTH\u2019S FINEST\nIt is Imposing from Every View\nPoint\nThe General Plea of Architecture\nTtMb lheitti Prate\u20144\n\u00bbP\u00abee la the Lettr la*\nWith practically all of the exterior\nwork completed the magnificent edl\nflce of the Plret Baptist Church con\ngregation stands out a monument\nworthy -of the splendid church which\nhas been shepherded by so many of the\nSouth's Illustrious divines In years\ngone by. The growth In strength, both\nIn religious life end worldy accom\nplishments. Is the result of the many\nyear's careful work on the part 'of\nthose who have been pastors of this\nflock, until now It Is preparing a house\nof worship which Is second to none\nIn the South.\nLocated on a prominent eminence\non Perry street between Soott and\nAlabama streets the magnificent dome\nof the structure, with Its red tiled cov\nering, catches the eye from almost\nany point In the city. Its domes and\nturrets, punctuating the eky line, re\nlive the tedtousneea of outline uaually\nfound In buildings of such proportions.\nIt le truly an imposing pile.\nIt will be many months before the\nbuilding is completed sufficiently t6\npermit of Its occupancy by the con\ngregation. All of the atone work has\nbeen completed, and the entire exter\nior. with the exception of some of\nthe ornamental Installations, has been\ncompleted. But Inside the church still\npresents a cavernous aspect, and for\nthe present work la suspended. The\nlecture room which la lteelf a large\nauditorium Is completed, Inside and Ik\nIn use by the congregation.\nThe main entrance to the edifice will\nbe from Perry street, although there\nwill be entrances from Alabama and\nSoott streets as well. The general\nplan of the architects tends toward*\nprofound spaces, the Immense dome\nabove the main andltorlum affords k\nlofty celling area of nearly one hun\ndred feet, and It Is In this great room\nthat the magnificence of tho construc\ntion will bs most lavishly displayed\nfrom viewing the Interior at present\nno Idea can be gained ot the magnifi\ncent Interior has been completed. The\necaffordtng has not yet been ttorn\naway, there is no flooring down, and\nthe bare arch, of Iierole proportions be\ntween the main auditorium and the\nSunday anhool rooms, Is without cov\nering.\nThe building committee Is not yst\nready to give to the public a full\ndescription of the church, rather re\nserving this for a surprise when tho\nday of dedication cornea. The general\narrangement, however, Is about the\nearns as any of the modern churches\nbut on a more extensive scale. The\nmain andltorlum will be eeparted front\nthe Sunday school room by a magnifi\ncent arch and slMlag doorway. Oc\ncupying a portion of this great space\nwill bs the handsome organ and choir\nloft\nThe baptismal will be to the left of\nthe pulpit, and It Is planned to be the\nmoot magnificent of Its hind In the\ncountry. It will be constructed of mar\nble throughout, with carved ornamen\ntione, etc. The seating capacity of the\nmain auditorium will be ample to ac\ncommodate the entire congregation\nand as many visitors as will usually\nbe found attending.\nIt will be possible to press Into\nservice the Sunday school room In\ncases of emergency. In this Sunday\nschool room there Is a gallery for the\nclasses while the teachers are In\ncharge. Following the lessens the\nclasses will be brought down Into the\nmain Sunday School room.\nThe only portion of the building\ncompleted to fsr ts the aesembly\nroom. This room Is now being used\nfor the regular services of the ehureh.\nThis room Is hemisphere In shape\nwith sixteen large white ornamentel\npillars In It. The door ts marble til\ned and the entire Interior is finished\nIs pure white. Connected with this\nroem le a lavatory for women, and a\nkitchen which ean be used In prepar\ning for church entertainments and re\nceptions. Thors Is also a kitchen up\nstairs connected with the Sunday school\nroom.\nIfi the Assembly room are hung the\nportraits of all of the former pastors\nof the First Baptist Church with the\nexception of one or two. They are ae\nfollows:\nLee Compere. 1829-13; S. D. Worth\nington, 18*4. (No portrait yeti\n.Tames H. DSVotle: Jease E.\nHartwell. 18*4-*8: William Cary\nCrab*. 18*9-41; Thomas Chilton. 184*;\nHenry Talhlrd, 1848-51: Isaac Taylor\nTichenor. 185*.80: Basil Manly. 18*0-43\nDavid William Owin 1888-78: Joseph\nBoardman Hawthorne. 1878-78; Augus\ntus Beverly Woodfln. 1880-88: Morton\nBryan Wharton. 1884-90; William Har\nris. 1890; George Boardman Edgar,\n1892-1900: Charles Averetta Stakeley,\n1900\u2014.\nNearly two hundred seats more are\nafforded In the assembly room now\nthan were obtainable in the old ehureh.\nThis room, however. Is not to be ueed\nfor services when the other rooms In\nthe church are completed. It will be\ndevoted to receptions, library, chart\nroom. etc.\nThroughout the church la to be fit\nted with all modern conveniences, auch\nas lavatories, retiring rooms, etc. The\nheating apparatus la In the cellar be\nneath the main auditorium. Steam will\nhe employed throughout the building\nfor heating purposes.\nThe structure Is entirely of brick,\nsteel and Georgia marble.\nsacola and Mobile. The tendency to\ncome here will be accelerated on this\nbasis alon*. even If there were not\nwaiting to be utilized the vast horse\npower of the Coosa River. Further\nmore. Montgomery is not yet receiv\ning a modicum of strength from the\nwealth waiting to be brought to It\nfrom the particularly rich group of\ncounties north and northeast, for thesa\nare more inaccessible to Montgomery,\nthough only a few miles away, than la\nAtlanta. When railroads and mines\nand water powers and waterways are\ndeveloped through Elmore, Coosa, Tal\nlapoosa. Clay and these and other\ncounties thus rendered tributary to\nMontgomery and its manufacturing en\nterprises, our growth will become tre\nmendous, rivaling the growth of any\nmanufacturing centre in the whole\nUnited States. Contrast Montgomery\nwith Atlanta and you see that it has a\nsafe, solid, enduring foundation of ma\nterial wealth. Atlanta has the spirit\nof growth, but has not such a reserve\nto fall back upon as baa Montgomery.\nContrast it with thriving New Eng,\nland cities like SDrlngftaldfl Bridge,\nport and so on. and you see that the\ntCeattaard ea Page TnJ","height":"27648","width":"20004"}}
